    {
      "id": "l3-to-be",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "The verb 'to be'",
      "body": "# to be: am / is / are\n\nEnglish uses three present forms of *to be*:\n\n| Subject | to be | Hindi |\n|---|---|---|\n| I | **am** | मैं हूँ |\n| you | **are** | आप हैं |\n| he / she / it | **is** | वह / यह है |\n| we / they | **are** | हम / वे हैं |\n\nSo: *I am a student.* (मैं एक छात्र हूँ।) · *She is from India.* (वह भारत से है।) · *They are happy.* (वे ख़ुश हैं।)\n\nMatch the form to the subject: **I → am**, **he/she/it → is**, **you/we/they → are**."
    },
